<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="2" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[264,1323,598,905]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,439,758,784]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[449,700,759,784]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Brachystegus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nikitini">
<emphasis box="[449,700,759,784]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Brachystegus nikitini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a species apparently closely related to 
<taxonomicName authority="Smith" authorityName="Smith" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Brachystegus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="basalis">
<emphasis box="[1204,1322,759,784]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">B. basalis</emphasis>
(Smith)
</taxonomicName>
in having a similar body structure, punctuation and coloration, but it distinctly differs from the latter in having a pair of subconical tubercles on the interocellar space, mostly red legs in male (presumable also in female) and unusual male sternal brushes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
